conbody.p:
You can issue a N1QL query by creating a CouchbaseN1qlQuery object
            using the CouchbaseN1qlQuery::fromString function. The function
            accepts the actual N1QL query string to be sent to the server. Once the query object has
            been created, you can pass it to the CouchbaseBucket::query method,
            which returns an array of result
            rows.$query = CouchbaseN1qlQuery::fromString('SELECT airportname FROM `travel-sample` LIMIT 10');
$rows = $bucket->query($query);
foreach ($rows as $row) {
    echo "Airport name is: " . $row->airportname . "\n";
}The
            content of the rows is dependent on the format of the query itself. In the example above
            we ask the server to return the airportname from each document, so we
            can expect an $row->airportname property to exist.

You can use N1QL placeholders in the query. Placeholders allow you to specify variable
            constraints for an otherwise constant query. To use placeholders, construct a
                CouchbaseN1qlQuery object with the base query string, and then
            supply placeholder values inside the options property within the query
            object.$query = CouchbaseN1qlQuery::fromString('SELECT fname, lname, age FROM default WHERE age > $age')
$query->options['$age'] = 22;
$bucket->query($query);
// ...
